swInterfaces.description: The private MIB module definition for Switch Interfaces.

swIfTable.name: swIfTable
swIfTable.description: Switch media specific information and configuration of the device interfaces.

swIfEntry.name: swIfEntry
swIfEntry.description: Defines the contents of each line in the swIfTable table.

swIfIndex.name: swIfIndex
swIfIndex.description: Index to the swIfTable. The interface defined by a particular value of this index is the same interface as identified by the same value of ifIndex (MIB II).

swIfPhysAddressType.name: swIfPhysAddressType
swIfPhysAddressType.description: This variable indicates whether the physical address assigned to this interface should be the default one or be chosen from the set of reserved physical addresses of the device.

swIfDuplexAdminMode.name: swIfDuplexAdminMode
swIfDuplexAdminMode.description: This variable specifies whether this interface should operate in half duplex or full duplex mode. This specification will take effect only if swIfSpeedDuplexAutoNegotiation is disabled. A value of 'none' is returned if a value of the variable hasn't been set.

swIfDuplexOperMode.name: swIfDuplexOperMode
swIfDuplexOperMode.description: This variable indicates whether this interface operates in half duplex or full duplex mode. This variable can have the values hybrid or unknown only for a trunk. unknown - only if trunk operative status is not present.

swIfBackPressureMode.name: swIfBackPressureMode
swIfBackPressureMode.description: This variable indicates whether this interface activates back pressure when congested.

swIfTaggedMode.name: swIfTaggedMode
swIfTaggedMode.description: If enable, this interface operates in tagged mode, i.e all frames sent out through this interface will have the 802.1Q header. If disabled the frames will not be tagged.

swIfTransceiverType.name: swIfTransceiverType
swIfTransceiverType.description: This variable indicates the transceiver type of this interface.

swIfLockAdminStatus.name: swIfLockAdminStatus
swIfLockAdminStatus.description: This variable indicates whether this interface should operate in locked or unlocked mode. In unlocked mode the device learns all MAC addresses from this port and forwards all frames arrived at this port. In locked mode no new MAC addresses are learned and only frames with known source MAC addresses are forwarded.

swIfLockOperStatus.name: swIfLockOperStatus
swIfLockOperStatus.description: This variable defines whether this interface operates in locked or unlocked mode. It is locked in each of the following two cases: 1) if swLockAdminStatus is set to locked 2) no IP/IPX interface is defined over this interface and no VLAN contains this interface. In unlocked mode the device learns all MAC addresses from this port and forwards all frames arrived at this port. In locked mode no new MAC addresses are learned and only frames with known source MAC addresses are forwarded.

swIfType.name: swIfType
swIfType.description: This variable specifies the type of interface.

swIfDefaultTag.name: swIfDefaultTag
swIfDefaultTag.description: This variable specifies the default VLAN tag which will be attached to outgoing frames if swIfTaggedMode for this interface is enabled.

swIfDefaultPriority.name: swIfDefaultPriority
swIfDefaultPriority.description: This variable specifies the default port priority.

swIfStatus.name: swIfStatus
swIfStatus.description: The status of a table entry. It is used to delete an entry from this table.

swIfFlowControlMode.name: swIfFlowControlMode
swIfFlowControlMode.description: on - Flow control will be enabled on this interface according to the IEEE 802.3x standard. off - Flow control is disabled. autoNegotiation - Flow control will be enabled or disabled on this interface. If enabled, it will operate as specified by the IEEE 802.3x standard. enabledRx - Flow control will be enabled on this interface for recieved frames. enabledTx - Flow control will be enabled on this interface for transmitted frames. An attempt to set this object to 'enabledRx(4)' or 'enabledTx(5)' will fail on interfaces that do not support operation at greater than 100 Mb/s. In any case, flow control can work only if swIfDuplexOperMode is full.

swIfSpeedAdminMode.name: swIfSpeedAdminMode
swIfSpeedAdminMode.description: This variable specifies the required speed of this interface in bits per second. This specification will take effect only if swIfSpeedDuplexAutoNegotiation is disabled. A value of 10 is returned for 10G. A value of 0 is returned if the value of the variable hasn't been set.

swIfSpeedDuplexAutoNegotiation.name: swIfSpeedDuplexAutoNegotiation
swIfSpeedDuplexAutoNegotiation.description: If enabled the speed and duplex mode will be set by the device through the autonegotiation process. Otherwise these characteristics will be set according to the values of swIfSpeedAdminMode and swIfSpeedDuplexAutoNegotiation.

swIfOperFlowControlMode.name: swIfOperFlowControlMode
swIfOperFlowControlMode.description: on - Flow control is enabled on this interface according to the IEEE 802.3x standard. off - Flow control is disabled. enabledRx - Flow control is enabled on this interface for recieved frames. enabledTx - Flow control is enabled on this interface for transmitted frames.

swIfOperSpeedDuplexAutoNegotiation.name: swIfOperSpeedDuplexAutoNegotiation
swIfOperSpeedDuplexAutoNegotiation.description: If enabled the speed and duplex are determined by the device through the autonegotiation process. If disabled these characteristics are determined according to the values of swIfSpeedAdminMode and swIfDuplexAdminMode. hybrid - only for a trunk. unknown - only for ports that there operative status is not present.

swIfOperBackPressureMode.name: swIfOperBackPressureMode
swIfOperBackPressureMode.description: This variable indicates the operative back pressure mode of this interface.

swIfAdminLockAction.name: swIfAdminLockAction
swIfAdminLockAction.description: This variable indicates which action this interface should be taken in locked mode and therefore relevant only in locked mode. Possible actions: discard(1) - every packet is dropped. forwardNormal(2) - every packet is forwarded according to the DST address. discardDisable(3) - drops the first packet and suspends the port.

swIfOperLockAction.name: swIfOperLockAction
swIfOperLockAction.description: This variable indicates which action this interface actually takes in locked mode and therefore relevant only in locked mode. Possible actions: discard(1) - every packet is dropped. forwardNormal(2) - every packet is forwarded according to the DST address. discardDisable(3) - drops the first packet and suspends the port.

swIfAdminLockTrapEnable.name: swIfAdminLockTrapEnable
swIfAdminLockTrapEnable.description: This variable indicates whether to create a SNMP trap in the locked mode.

swIfOperLockTrapEnable.name: swIfOperLockTrapEnable
swIfOperLockTrapEnable.description: This variable indicates whether a SNMP trap can be created in the locked mode.

swIfOperSuspendedStatus.name: swIfOperSuspendedStatus
swIfOperSuspendedStatus.description: This variable indicates whether the port is suspended or not due to some feature. After reboot this value is false

swIfLockOperTrapCount.name: swIfLockOperTrapCount
swIfLockOperTrapCount.description: This variable indicates the trap counter status per ifIndex (i.e. number of received packets since the last trap sent due to a packet which was received on this ifIndex). It's relevant only in locked mode while trap is enabled.

swIfLockAdminTrapFrequency.name: swIfLockAdminTrapFrequency
swIfLockAdminTrapFrequency.description: This variable indicates the minimal frequency (in seconds) of sending a trap per ifIndex. It's relevant only in locked mode and in trap enabled.

swIfReActivate.name: swIfReActivate
swIfReActivate.description: This variable reactivates (enables) an ifIndex (which was suspended)

swIfAdminMdix.name: swIfAdminMdix
swIfAdminMdix.description: The configuration is on a physical port, not include trunks. cross - The interface should force crossover. normal - The interface should not force crossover. auto - Auto mdix is enabled on the interface.

swIfOperMdix.name: swIfOperMdix
swIfOperMdix.description: cross - The interface is in crossover mode. normal - The interface is not in crossover mode. unknown - Only for port that its operative status is not present or down.

swIfHostMode.name: swIfHostMode
swIfHostMode.description: This variable indicates the 802.1X host mode of a port. Relevant when the port's 802.1X control is auto. In addtion multiple-auth was added.

swIfSingleHostViolationAdminAction.name: swIfSingleHostViolationAdminAction
swIfSingleHostViolationAdminAction.description: This variable indicates which action this interface should take in single authorized. Possible actions: discard - every packet is dropped. forwardNormal - every packet is forwarded according to the DST address. discardDisable - drops the first packet and suspends the port.

swIfSingleHostViolationOperAction.name: swIfSingleHostViolationOperAction
swIfSingleHostViolationOperAction.description: This variable indicates which action this interface actually takes in single authorized. Possible actions: discard(1) - every packet is dropped. forwardNormal(2) - every packet is forwarded according to the DST address. discardDisable(3) - drops the first packet and suspends the port.

swIfSingleHostViolationAdminTrapEnable.name: swIfSingleHostViolationAdminTrapEnable
swIfSingleHostViolationAdminTrapEnable.description: This variable indicates whether to create a SNMP trap in single authorized.

swIfSingleHostViolationOperTrapEnable.name: swIfSingleHostViolationOperTrapEnable
swIfSingleHostViolationOperTrapEnable.description: This variable indicates whether a SNMP trap can be created in the single authorized.

swIfSingleHostViolationOperTrapCount.name: swIfSingleHostViolationOperTrapCount
swIfSingleHostViolationOperTrapCount.description: This variable indicates the trap counter status per ifIndex (i.e. number of received packets since the last trap sent due to a packet which was received on this ifIndex). It's relevant only in single authorized while trap is enabled.

swIfSingleHostViolationAdminTrapFrequenc.name: swIfSingleHostViolationAdminTrapFrequency
swIfSingleHostViolationAdminTrapFrequenc.description: This variable indicates the minimal frequency (in seconds) of sending a trap per ifIndex. It's relevant only in single authorized and in trap enabled. A value of 0 means that trap is disabled.

swIfLockLimitationMode.name: swIfLockLimitationMode
swIfLockLimitationMode.description: This variable indicates what is the learning limitation on the locked interface. Possible values: disabled - learning is stopped. The dynamic addresses associated with the port are not aged out or relearned on other port as long as the port is locked. dynamic - dynamic addresses can be learned up to the maximum dynamic addresses allowed on the port. Relearning and aging of the dynamic addresses are enabled. The learned addresses aren't kept after reset. secure-permanent - secure addresses can be learned up to the maximum addresses allowed on the port. Relearning and aging of addresses are disabled. The learned addresses are kept after reset. secure-delete-on-reset - secure addresses can be learned up to the maximum addresses allowed on the port. Relearning and aging of addresses are disabled. The learned addresses are not kept after reset.

swIfLockMaxMacAddresses.name: swIfLockMaxMacAddresses
swIfLockMaxMacAddresses.description: This variable defines the maximum number of dynamic addresses that can be asscoiated with the locked interface. It isn't relevant in disabled limitation mode.

swIfLockMacAddressesCount.name: swIfLockMacAddressesCount
swIfLockMacAddressesCount.description: This variable indicates the actual number of dynamic addresses that can be asscoiated with the locked interface. It isn't relevant in disabled limitation mode.

swIfAdminSpeedDuplexAutoNegotiationLocal.name: swIfAdminSpeedDuplexAutoNegotiationLocalCapabilities
swIfAdminSpeedDuplexAutoNegotiationLocal.description: Administrative auto negotiation capabilities of the interface that can be advertised when swIfSpeedDuplexAutoNegotiation is enabled. default bit means advertise all the port's capabilities according to its type.

swIfOperSpeedDuplexAutoNegotiationLocalC.name: swIfOperSpeedDuplexAutoNegotiationLocalCapabilities
swIfOperSpeedDuplexAutoNegotiationLocalC.description: Operative auto negotiation capabilities of the remote link. unknown bit means that port operative status is not up.

swIfSpeedDuplexNegotiationRemoteCapabili.name: swIfSpeedDuplexNegotiationRemoteCapabilities
swIfSpeedDuplexNegotiationRemoteCapabili.description: Operative auto negotiation capabilities of the remote link. unknown bit means that port operative status is not up, or auto negotiation process not complete, or remote link is not auto negotiation able.

swIfAdminComboMode.name: swIfAdminComboMode
swIfAdminComboMode.description: This variable specifies the administrative mode of a combo Ethernet interface.

swIfOperComboMode.name: swIfOperComboMode
swIfOperComboMode.description: This variable specifies the operative mode of a combo Ethernet interface.

swIfAutoNegotiationMasterSlavePreference.name: swIfAutoNegotiationMasterSlavePreference
swIfAutoNegotiationMasterSlavePreference.description: This variable specifies the administrative mode of the Maste-Slave preference in auto negotiation.

swIfMibVersion.name: swIfMibVersion
swIfMibVersion.description: The swIfTable Mib's version, the current version is 3.

swIfPortLockSupport.name: swIfPortLockSupport
swIfPortLockSupport.description: indicates if the locked port package is supported.

swIfPortLockActionSupport.name: swIfPortLockActionSupport
swIfPortLockActionSupport.description: indicates which port lock actions are supported: (bit 0 is the most significant bit) bit 0 - discard bit 1 - forwardNormal bit 2 - discardDisable

swIfPortLockTrapSupport.name: swIfPortLockTrapSupport
swIfPortLockTrapSupport.description: indicates with which port lock actions the trap option is supported (e.g. discard indicates that trap is supported only when the portlock action is discard): (bit 0 is the most significant bit) bit 0 - discard bit 1 - forwardNormal bit 2 - discardDisable

swIfPortLockIfRangeEntry.name: swIfPortLockIfRangeEntry
swIfPortLockIfRangeEntry.description: Defines the contents of each line in the swIfPortLockIfRangeTable table.

swIfPortLockIfRange.name: swIfPortLockIfRange
swIfPortLockIfRange.description: The set of interfaces to which the port lock parameters should be configured

swIfPortLockIfRangeLockStatus.name: swIfPortLockIfRangeLockStatus
swIfPortLockIfRangeLockStatus.description: This variable indicates whether the interfaces range should operate in locked or unlocked mode. In unlocked mode the device learns all MAC addresses from these interfaces and forwards all frames arrived at these interfaces. In locked mode no new MAC addresses are learned and only frames with known source MAC addresses are forwarded.

swIfPortLockIfRangeAction.name: swIfPortLockIfRangeAction
swIfPortLockIfRangeAction.description: This variable indicates which action for these interfaces should be take in locked mode and therefore relevant only in locked mode. Possible actions: discard(1) - every packet is dropped. forwardNormal(2) - every packet is forwarded according to the DST address. discardDisable(3) - drops the first packet and suspends the port.

swIfPortLockIfRangeTrapEn.name: swIfPortLockIfRangeTrapEn
swIfPortLockIfRangeTrapEn.description: This variable indicates whether to create a SNMP trap in the locked mode.

swIfPortLockIfRangeTrapFreq.name: swIfPortLockIfRangeTrapFreq
swIfPortLockIfRangeTrapFreq.description: This variable indicates the minimal frequency (in seconds) of sending a trap for these interfaces. It's relevant only in locked mode and in trap enabled.

swIfExtTable.name: swIfExtTable
swIfExtTable.description: Display information and configuration of the device interfaces.

swIfExtEntry.name: swIfExtEntry
swIfExtEntry.description: Defines the contents of each row in the swIfExtTable.

swIfExtSFPSpeed.name: swIfExtSFPSpeed
swIfExtSFPSpeed.description: Configure speed of an SFP Ethernet interface.

rlIfMibVersion.name: rlIfMibVersion
rlIfMibVersion.description: MIB's version, the current version is 1.

rlIfNumOfPhPorts.name: rlIfNumOfPhPorts
rlIfNumOfPhPorts.description: Total number of physical ports on this device (including all stack units)

rlIfMapOfOnPhPorts.name: rlIfMapOfOnPhPorts
rlIfMapOfOnPhPorts.description: Each bit in this octet string indicates that the correspondig port's ifOperStatus is ON if set. The mapping of port number to bits in this octet string is as follows: The port with the L2 interface number 1 is mapped to the least significant bit of the 1st octet, the port with L2 ifNumber 2 to the next significant bit in the 1st octet, port 8 to the most-significant bit of the in the 1st octet, port 9 to the least significant bit of the 2nd octet, etc. and in general, port n to bit corresponding to 2**((n mod 8) -1) in byte n/8 + 1

rlIfClearPortMibCounters.name: rlIfClearPortMibCounters
rlIfClearPortMibCounters.description: Each bit that is set in this portList represent a port that its mib counters should be reset.

rlIfNumOfUserDefinedPorts.name: rlIfNumOfUserDefinedPorts
rlIfNumOfUserDefinedPorts.description: The number of user defined ports on this device.

rlIfFirstOutOfBandIfIndex.name: rlIfFirstOutOfBandIfIndex
rlIfFirstOutOfBandIfIndex.description: First ifIndex of out-of-band port. This scalar exists only the device has out of band ports.

rlIfNumOfLoopbackPorts.name: rlIfNumOfLoopbackPorts
rlIfNumOfLoopbackPorts.description: The number of loopback ports on this device.

rlIfFirstLoopbackIfIndex.name: rlIfFirstLoopbackIfIndex
rlIfFirstLoopbackIfIndex.description: First ifIndex of loopback port. This scalar will exists only if rlIfNumOfLoopbackPorts is different from 0.

rlIfExistingPortList.name: rlIfExistingPortList
rlIfExistingPortList.description: Indicates which ports/trunks exist in the system. It doesn't indicate which are present.

rlIfBaseMACAddressPerIfIndex.name: rlIfBaseMACAddressPerIfIndex
rlIfBaseMACAddressPerIfIndex.description: Indicates if the system will assign a unique MAC per Ethernet port or not.

rlFlowControlCascadeMode.name: rlFlowControlCascadeMode
rlFlowControlCascadeMode.description: enable disable flow control on cascade ports

rlFlowControlCascadeType.name: rlFlowControlCascadeType
rlFlowControlCascadeType.description: define which type of ports will be affected by flow control on cascade ports

rlFlowControlRxPerSystem.name: rlFlowControlRxPerSystem
rlFlowControlRxPerSystem.description: define if flow control RX is supported per system.

rlCascadePortProtectionAction.name: rlCascadePortProtectionAction
rlCascadePortProtectionAction.description: As a result of this set all of the local cascade ports will stop being consider unstable and will be force up.

rlManagementIfIndex.name: rlManagementIfIndex
rlManagementIfIndex.description: Specify L2 bound management interface index in a single IP address system when configurable management interface is supported.

rlIfClearStackPortsCounters.name: rlIfClearStackPortsCounters
rlIfClearStackPortsCounters.description: As a result of this set all counters of all external cascade ports will be cleared.

rlIfClearPortMacAddresses.name: rlIfClearPortMacAddresses
rlIfClearPortMacAddresses.description: if port is non secure, its all dynamic MAC addresses are cleared. if port is secure, its all secure MAC addresses which have learned or configured are cleared.

rlIfCutThroughPacketLength.name: rlIfCutThroughPacketLength
rlIfCutThroughPacketLength.description: The default packet length that is assigned to a packet in the Cut-Through mode.

rlIfCutPriorityZero.name: rlIfCutPriorityZero
rlIfCutPriorityZero.description: Enable or disable cut-Through for priority 0.

rlIfCutPriorityOne.name: rlIfCutPriorityOne
rlIfCutPriorityOne.description: Enable or disable cut-Through for priority 1.

rlIfCutPriorityTwo.name: rlIfCutPriorityTwo
rlIfCutPriorityTwo.description: Enable or disable cut-Through for priority 2.

rlIfCutPriorityThree.name: rlIfCutPriorityThree
rlIfCutPriorityThree.description: Enable or disable cut-Through for priority 3.

rlIfCutPriorityFour.name: rlIfCutPriorityFour
rlIfCutPriorityFour.description: Enable or disable cut-Through for priority 4.

rlIfCutPriorityFive.name: rlIfCutPriorityFive
rlIfCutPriorityFive.description: Enable or disable cut-Through for priority 5.

rlIfCutPrioritySix.name: rlIfCutPrioritySix
rlIfCutPrioritySix.description: Enable or disable cut-Through for priority 6.

rlIfCutPrioritySeven.name: rlIfCutPrioritySeven
rlIfCutPrioritySeven.description: Enable or disable cut-Through for priority 7.

rlIfCutThroughTable.name: rlIfCutThroughTable
rlIfCutThroughTable.description: Information and configuration of cut-through feature.

rlIfCutThroughEntry.name: rlIfCutThroughEntry
rlIfCutThroughEntry.description: Defines the contents of each line in the swIfTable table.

rlIfCutThroughPriorityEnable.name: rlIfCutThroughPriorityEnable
rlIfCutThroughPriorityEnable.description: Enable or disable cut-through for a priority for an interface.

rlIfCutThroughUntaggedEnable.name: rlIfCutThroughUntaggedEnable
rlIfCutThroughUntaggedEnable.description: Enable or disable cut-through for untagged packets for an interface.

rlIfCutThroughOperMode.name: rlIfCutThroughOperMode
rlIfCutThroughOperMode.description: Operational mode of spesific cut-through interface.

rlCutThroughPacketLength.name: rlCutThroughPacketLength
rlCutThroughPacketLength.description: The default packet length that is assigned to a packet in the Cut-Through mode.

rlCutThroughPacketLengthAfterReset.name: rlCutThroughPacketLengthAfterReset
rlCutThroughPacketLengthAfterReset.description: The default packet length that is assigned to a packet in the Cut-Through mode after reset.

rlCutThroughEnableAfterReset.name: rlCutThroughEnableAfterReset
rlCutThroughEnableAfterReset.description: Cut-Through global enable mode after reset.

rlFlowControlMode.name: rlFlowControlMode
rlFlowControlMode.description: Define which mode will be enabled on flow control enabled ports. The interfaces with enabled flow control will receive pause frames, but will not send flow control pause frames Send-receive: The interfaces with enabled flow control will receive and send pause frames. Receive-only: The interfaces with enabled flow control will receive pause frames, but will not send flow control pause frames.
